BSE - JAPAN: NEW CASE, MILK REPLACERS
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Fri 21 Dec 2007
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-12/21/content_7290974.htm>

The Fisheries Ministry said on Friday [21 Dec 2007] that a cow in
northern Japan's Hokkaido had been tested positive for mad cow disease.
It was the 34th case of mad cow disease confirmed so far in the country.
According to the ministry's press release, the 15-year-old cow was
born in western Japan's Shimane Prefecture and was raised in
Hokkaido. After it was killed on Wednesday [19 Dec 2007], the beef
was tested positive for mad cow disease during check-up by a local
meat inspection institution.
The result was confirmed shortly after further testing at Hokkaido
University and another farming college nearby.
The cow was the oldest one in all the mad cow disease cases in Japan.
All of the cow's meat and gut were incinerated before entering
market, the press release said.
[Editor: Yan Liang]
--
Communicated by:
Terry S. Singeltary Sr.
<flounder9@verizon.net>
[OIE's (World Organization for Animal Health) website includes the
following data concerning the previous 33 BSE (bovine spongiform
encephalitis) cases reported from Japan:
2001: 3(*); 2002: 2; 2003: 4(**); 2004: 5; 2005: 7; 2006: 10 ; 2007
(as of 2 July 2007): 2
* one clinical case, 2 detected as result of screening at the abattoir.
** the 9th case was a bullock aged 21 months.
The said website provides also the data on the annual incidence rate
of BSE ("Number of indigenous cases per million bovines aged over 24
months") in OIE Member Countries that have reported cases.
Japan's data from the table are the following:
2001: 1.44; 2002: 0.97; 2003: 1.96; 2004: 2.491; 2005: 3.575; 2006:
5.018. This gradual increase (which seems to have peaked in 2006) is
different from all other BSE-infected countries, where the incidence
had peaked earlier. The table is available at
<http://oie.int/eng/info/en_esbincidence.htm>. - Mod.AS]
