[3]
Date: Mon 17 Dec 2007
Source: Agrarisch Dagblad [in Dutch, trans. Mod.AS, edited]
<http://www.agd.nl/1042509/Nieuws/Artikel/Japans-BSE-onderzoek-wijst-weer-naar-Nederland.htm>

A Japanese research into the cause of the BSE-epidemic indicates
again that milk replacers of Dutch origin may have been the source of
infection.
The Japanese Ministry of Agriculture has published a new report,
which states that 13 out of the 32 investigated BSE cases could have
been caused by powdered milk of Dutch origin. The total number of BSE
cases, so far, is 33.
The Japanese blamed the Netherlands initially in 2002. This led to
intensive discussions between the Dutch and Japanese Veterinary
authorities. A Japanese delegation visited Dutch processing plants to
see how the production of milk replacers was carried out here.
Research in Germany's Bavaria, in 2004, was also indicative of the
possibility that ingredients in calves' milk replacers could have
been the infective vehicle of the lethal bovine disease.
The Dutch authorities are of the opinion that it is not likely that
powdered milk from the Netherlands was contaminated, while it is
likely that meat-and-bone meal was the source. Had the Dutch products
indeed been infective, this should have been manifested in the
Netherlands as well, since the Dutch calves received the same
product. No connection between the feeding with milk replacers and
incidence of BSE could be established. On the other hand, such
connection could indeed be demonstrated between the inclusion of
meat-meals in animal concentrates and BSE cases.
Japan does not exclude the possibility that meat-and-bone meals were
also source of the BSE outbreaks. In 1990, Great Britain indicated to
Japan the possible hazard of BSE spread via meat-and-bone meals.
[Byline: Jan Braakman]
